content.text: Getting enough physical activity can be a challenge, but we’re here to help. With your health goals in mind, we can make an activity plan to help you master skills using achievable action steps. You can learn to be more active and stay motivated along the way. First, we need to see if this program is a good fit for you.
Are you able to walk for exercise?
Thanks for letting us know. Being able to exercise is key to this program.

choice.text: Setting a good example for my family

content.text: Being more active can have lots of benefits, both mentally and physically. Which of the following is the most important to you?

choice.text: I sit or stand most of the day.
I sit or stand part of the day, but am moving around for part of the day as well.

content.text: Which of the following best describes your typical day?

Moderate-intensity activity
During moderate-intensity activities, you’re able to hold a conversation, but you’re working hard enough to raise your heart rate and break a sweat. Brisk walking, casual swimming and doubles tennis are examples of moderate-intensity activities.
In a typical week, what is the average amount of time you spend doing moderate-intensity physical activity?

Vigorous-intensity activity
During vigorous-intensity activities, you’re breathing hard and fast, and your heart rate has gone up quite a bit. If you’re working at this level, you won’t be able to say more than a few words without pausing for a breath. These types of activities include running, bicycling, swimming laps, and weight circuit training.
In a typical week, what is the average amount of time you spend doing vigorous-intensity physical activity?
How about strength-training exercises, such as using free weights, weight machines, or resistance bands? How often do you do those?

The current Physical Activity Guidelines for Americans are to do 150 minutes of moderate activity or 75 minutes of vigorous activity a week, plus strength training 2 days a week.

We'll help you build the skills you'll need to develop healthy lifestyle habits.

How confident are you that you can do it?

Exercise just doesn't seem that important.

I live for today and don't worry about tomorrow.

content.text: Now, which of the following keep you from getting regular physical activity?

choice.text: ACCOMPLISHMENT - mastery of knowledge, skills, abilities
ADVENTURE - seeking big rewards from big risks
BALANCE - inner peace, centered, moderate, perspective
COMMUNITY - participating in groups that share your neighborhood, type of work, or beliefs
COURAGE - testing limits, facing difficulties with resilience
CREATIVITY - imagination, new ways of doing and seeing
FUN - enjoyment, playfulness, sense of play
GENEROSITY - sharing time, money, and energy with others
GROWTH - forward motion in personal development
INTEGRITY - honesty, strength of character, and justice in dealings with others
RELATIONSHIPS - strong, active bonds with family and friends
RESPECT - fair treatment, valuing individuals for uniqueness
SPIRITUALITY - connection with something larger than the "here and now"
SERVICE - to be of assistance and support to a person or cause

content.text: We'd like to ask you about something that might surprise you – what drives you? It's important to tie changes in your life to the things that are most important to you. So what do you consider to be your core values? Please choose the ones that mean the most to you and that define you as a person.

In your Building Motivation skill, you'll see how your core values fit right in with having an active lifestyle.

A support system is really important when you're making big changes. It can be made up of one person, or a bunch of people who you turn to for different needs. Or, you might rely on other resources for support, entirely. We'd like to learn a little more about your support system.

choice.text: I don’t get support from these people.

content.text: In general, how satisfied are you with the support you get from your family and friends?

choice.text: I'd rather not ask for support.

content.text: Having someone in your corner can be a huge help. Who would you like to support you while you make changes in your exercise?
Of the people you spend most of your time with, about how many exercise regularly?

content.text: There are so many ways to be active that you can make it either a social experience or a solo journey – or a bit of both. While you’re getting your exercise, which would you like to do?

It can be a challenge to become more active, but getting support can help you be successful.

When it comes to being active, it helps when you feel energized. Let's look a little closer at your level of energy and the quality of your sleep.
How much energy do you feel you've had over the past week?
Over the past week, how much sleep did you generally get in each 24-hour period?

content.helpText: Choose a lower number if you haven’t been sleeping well. Choose a higher number if you have been sleeping well.
content.text: How would you rate the overall quality of your sleep?

Feeling energized can be helpful when it comes to being active. And being active in the long run may even help you feel more alert and sleep better.

We have a few more questions that will help us determine how your health affects your day-to-day life.
Are you currently employed (working for pay)?

We’re going to ask you to think about how your health problems affect your ability to do your regular daily activities. By regular activities, we mean the usual things you do day-to-day, such as work around the house, shopping, child care, exercising, studying, etc. Think about times you were limited in the amount or kind of activities you could do, and times you accomplished less than you would like because of your health. If health problems affected your activities only a little or not at all, choose a low number. Choose a high number if health problems affected your activities a great deal.

Health problems completely prevented me from doing my daily activities
